issues.description: Constructor parameter order for ExcellenceLand is inconsistent between the problem statement (UML + task instructions) and the solution. The problem statement requires constructors to take attributes in the same order as in the UML (first attribute on top => first parameter). The UML lists ExcellenceLand attributes as: 1) excellencyLevel: double, 2) excellentEnough: boolean. The task text additionally states there should be a private List<Ride> rides attribute. Following the UML + instruction, a constructor would be expected with parameters in the order (double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides). However, the solution implements the constructor as (List<Ride> rides, boolean excellentEnough, double excellencyLevel), placing rides first and excellencyLevel last. This discrepancy contradicts the explicit constructor-order rule in the problem statement and will confuse students about the required parameter order (and likely cause test failures if tests check for the specified order).
issues.suggested_fix: Make the constructor parameter order consistent with the UML and the explicit instruction. Either: (A) Change the constructor in the solution and template to (double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides) and assign fields accordingly; or (B) update the problem statement to explicitly state the intended constructor parameter order (e.g., that rides should come first) so that the requirement matches the solution. Option A is recommended to follow the UML attribute order rule.
